00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:49.569
Rick March: you know, thing that they, you know, the rack that they put on the donkey's back to tie bundles to, and, you know, she, you know, so I was also, you know, kind of hearing these stories. I think all of this stuff contributed to a mentality that resulted in me becoming a folklorist.

153
00:22:49.570 --> 00:22:50.410
Julie Stout: Hmm.

154
00:22:50.990 --> 00:22:58.450
Rick March: And, When I, when I, Graduated from high school.

155
00:22:58.850 --> 00:23:17.009
Rick March: the Vietnam War was going on, and if you didn't go right into college and get what was called a 2S deferment for full-time college students, you would be eligible to be drafted. You'd be 1Y… no, no, 1A. 1A was ready to, you know, fresh meat for the Army.

156
00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:20.750
Rick March: Oh. And so, so, you know, I, I, I…

157
00:23:20.800 --> 00:23:25.279
Julie Stout: Didn't really know what I wanted to study, but I went to UCLA initially.

158
00:23:25.280 --> 00:23:27.910
Rick March: Staying at home.

159
00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:47.949
Rick March: And part of the reason was, you know, there was this thing in the 60s with all the rock bands. In the early 60s, because my oldest brother had been kind of an acolyte of Pete Seeger and his music, and he played banjo, and he played union songs, my family was involved with the union movement.

160
00:23:48.050 --> 00:24:07.060
Rick March: you know, this whole folk music thing, Peter, Paul, and Mary, Kingston Tree, all these were these, you know, I got interested in folk and bluegrass music, and I played guitar and mandolin, and the mandolin came because I was also playing ethnic music, Croatian music, on that.

161
00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:11.760
Rick March: Anyway, the,

162
00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:18.419
Rick March: Beatles came along, and they were on Ed Sullivan. We all, all us folkies.

163
00:24:18.630 --> 00:24:23.000
Rick March: Got freaked out and said, wow, let's get electric guitars, you know?

164
00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:28.050
Rick March: And so, I was in a rock band that was, you know, playing as a…

165
00:24:28.050 --> 00:24:52.999
Rick March: as the local warm-up band for some, some, other, you know, like, we warmed up for… there was a band called The Doors that, had, Sky Jim Morrison, who became kind of a rock legend, died young, stupidly. One of my friends who was in bands with me, Kenny Edwards, became the main bass player for Linda Ronstadt's band through most of his

166
00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.120
Rick March: his career.

167
00:24:54.120 --> 00:25:09.820
Rick March: You know, there's a number… a number of musicians that I dealt with. We hung out at this folk club called the Ashgrove, and so a guy named Rye Cooter was a good guitarist and had a career. There was a guy that used the stage name Taj Mahal.

168
00:25:09.890 --> 00:25:16.020
Rick March: who, you know, hung out there. So, you know, we… I was in this music scene, and that's why, although…

169
00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:17.749
Julie Stout: In college, right?

170
00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:31.770
Rick March: Yeah, yeah, yeah, my last years of high school and early… my first two years… so I wanted to stay in Hollywood at that time, because we hoped that our band would get, you know, a recording contract, and in those days, you couldn't…

171
00:25:31.770 --> 00:25:49.629
Rick March: you know, the record companies had complete control. It wasn't like now, where you can get, you know, good digital recordings, you can do all sorts of stuff on your own, and put things up on the internet, and, you know, none of that existed. What you did was, you had to pay to go into a studio, get a tape made.

172
00:25:50.900 --> 00:26:00.809
Rick March: Then you had to seal it up with all kinds of wax and string, and and then you mailed it to yourself.

173
00:26:00.810 --> 00:26:11.979
Rick March: so that it had a copyright date stamped on it, so that you could prove that you… you had written the songs and stuff. That was… that was kind of… you know… Anyway.

174
00:26:11.980 --> 00:26:16.699
Julie Stout: Did you, did you study, did you study music in college, or was this just a science?

175
00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:19.370
Rick March: Yeah, I studied anthropology.

176
00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:23.429
Rick March: I studied anthropology. I started out…

177
00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:40.820
Rick March: I started out thinking, because my eldest brother was a physics professor, and my next brother started out in geology, and then he moved eventually to Slavic languages, but I started out as a biology major, because I really liked my biology teacher in high school.

178
00:26:41.260 --> 00:26:54.090
Rick March: And then… and then I went into calculus, and I was… I was lousy. I wasn't the best math student. I, and then I… so I… I… I drifted, to anthropology. And,

179
00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:58.379
Rick March: That was good, again, for getting me into the folklore,

180
00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:06.060
Rick March: The UCLA had a professor in the anthro department named Ellen Dundees.

181
00:27:06.160 --> 00:27:17.219
Rick March: who is a… became a well-known folklorist in that he was… used Freudian approach as his… his thing, and he was at,

182
00:27:17.420 --> 00:27:26.119
Rick March: Oh, no, wait, well, no, he was… Dundee's was up at Berkeley, I misspoke. Yeah, it was Wayland Hand, who else was the…

183
00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:37.730
Rick March: there were… there were a couple more people. Yeah, they had the John Edwards Memorial Foundation, there was a country music archive, at UCLA. Dk Wilgis, there's a…

184
00:27:38.300 --> 00:27:45.950
Rick March: So there were these folklorists teaching at UCLA, and I took their courses as part of my anthro major.

185
00:27:46.050 --> 00:28:04.159
Rick March: And then when I went up, after 2 years, all the action seemed to be moved up to the Bay Area. That's where all the cool bands, you know, the San Francisco hippie scene had started, the psychedelic bands, all this stuff. And… and then also all the political agitation,

186
00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:22.860
Rick March: UCLA is kind of tucked away in this wealthy neighborhood, Westwood, and not close to things, whereas the Berkeley campus is right there in Berkeley, and there had been all, you know, the free speech movement, all this stuff, you know, which fired us up, you know.

187
00:28:22.860 --> 00:28:38.410
Rick March: We'd hop in a car, you know, 4 or 5 of us, and drive up, you know, the 400 miles to Berkeley to participate in, you know, peace marches and, you know, civil rights-related things.

188
00:28:38.430 --> 00:28:50.379
Rick March: So I, I was, I was, you know, ready to get out of my parents' house. And, so my junior and senior years, I was at Cal Berkeley.

189
00:28:50.450 --> 00:28:52.350
Julie Stout: And.

190
00:28:52.440 --> 00:29:00.510
Rick March: you know, that was… that was, influential on me, and I… I wound up using my music. I was in a street theater group called Agitprop.

191
00:29:00.530 --> 00:29:15.690
Rick March: where we were… we were encouraging people to resist the draft for the Vietnam War, by… by doing these street theater little plays, and we went around, actually, to high schools and junior colleges.

192
00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:23.790
Rick March: And had these little short plays that were 5 or 10 minutes long, because we'd, you know, illegally go onto the school campus.

193
00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:37.299
Rick March: Present this play, pass out some leaflets, and then, you know, one of us was assigned to argue with, like, the… the vice principal that came out to kick us out to… until we were able to, you know, just.

194
00:29:37.300 --> 00:29:49.979
Julie Stout: jump in the cars and go away. So, you know… Did you, during your degree, did you focus on, like, ethnomusicology a little bit, or was it… like, what was your focus in anthropology?

195
00:29:50.050 --> 00:29:57.430
Rick March: Well, you know, there wasn't… there wasn't anything like what later became known as applied anthropology.

196
00:29:57.430 --> 00:29:58.130
Julie Stout: Mmm…

197
00:29:58.130 --> 00:30:09.090
Rick March: you know, it was all strictly teaching you to do an ethnography. Your goal was to go off to New Guinea or someplace, you know, parachute into a village.

198
00:30:09.130 --> 00:30:22.790
Rick March: you know, hire a translator and, you know, interview people on their kinship systems. You know, that was the emphasis. And, I was… there was a… there was a right-wing

199
00:30:22.790 --> 00:30:39.190
Rick March: superintendent of education for California at that time, who notably went on the news and said that our campus at Berkeley has become a four-year course in sex, drugs, and treason.

200
00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:48.060
Rick March: And so, when people asked me what I was majoring in at Berkeley, I would always say, well, you know, the usual, sex, drugs, and countries, and…

201
00:30:48.060 --> 00:31:00.350
Rick March: You know, I'm lucky, I'm lucky that I graduated. I did enough to pass all my courses, and I think my GPA wound up at 2.6, because I was spending all my time

202
00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:10.549
Rick March: Going around, you know, doing all this, you know, move… you know, political movement-type things, you know, and…

203
00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:21.190
Rick March: And so I was… I was the guitarist for the street theater group, and we made up all these songs, and you know, they were parodies of things, you know, like Gilbert and Sullivan.

204
00:31:21.190 --> 00:31:37.890
Rick March: You know, we did one that was, called Moby Mao, the Great Red Whale, which was about that, that, you know, LBJ, Lyndon Johnson, the president at the time, was, was actually in Vietnam, you know, trying to start a war with China, you know, and so he had, you know.

205
00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:47.730
Rick March: you know, Captain LB leading the… you know, we made up these metaphorical plays that… some of them were pretty good, it's too bad. I think… I think…

206
00:31:48.140 --> 00:32:04.670
Rick March: one of them got recorded a little bit in a… a guy made kind of a low-budget exploitation movie about Berkeley weirdos, that they filmed us in… it's a little bit of one of our plays. It's in the Bancroft Library.

207
00:32:05.350 --> 00:32:12.620
Rick March: in Berkeley, but I don't know if there's any copy of it anywhere else, and they wouldn't even let me take a screenshot of it, they'd let me watch.

208
00:32:12.620 --> 00:32:13.105
Julie Stout: So…

209
00:32:13.590 --> 00:32:26.110
Rick March: They were so strict about, you know, copyright issues. But anyway, yeah, so, you know, this was the environment I was in, and then I graduated, and it was, oh shit, now, now…

210
00:32:26.110 --> 00:32:26.640
Julie Stout: What do I do?

211
00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:42.029
Rick March: Now, there goes my draft affirmment. So, I thought that maybe teaching… there was this program in Los Angeles, in the Black neighborhood, in the South Central Los Angeles, which was generally called Watts nationally, because

212
00:32:42.360 --> 00:32:55.030
Rick March: part of that neighborhood was Watts, and there was the Watts Riot in 1965. It was one of the first of these big urban riots. So anyway, I took a job where they were… they would hire anybody with a college degree.

213
00:32:55.140 --> 00:33:02.249
Rick March: who was willing to start taking education-related courses to get a teacher's credential, you know.

214
00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:16.839
Rick March: if you were willing to start teaching in schools in South Central LA. And these schools, you know, were, 90% to 99% African American students.

215
00:33:17.030 --> 00:33:25.450
Rick March: And so I thought, hey, okay, I'll do that, and maybe that would be considered an essential enough occupation I could get a drafter from it.

216
00:33:25.580 --> 00:33:26.739
Rick March: But,

217
00:33:27.120 --> 00:33:45.260
Rick March: Anyway, I didn't work out at that. I… I… I wasn't, the principal was, you know, what we called in those days an Oreo. It was, you know, black on the outside, white on the inside. And he wanted… he wanted us to be… well, he said, Mr. March.

218
00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:53.849
Rick March: The most important thing you have to, emphasize is classroom control. You know, if you have to spend, you know.

219
00:33:53.980 --> 00:34:13.829
Rick March: 90% of your time on classroom control, which meant making the kids sit still and fold their hands, you know? You know, I want you to do it. In fact, you have to spend 100% of your time on classroom control, you know, so, you know, and I was trying to be the groovy guy that the kids would like, and so, you know, like,

220
00:34:13.929 --> 00:34:21.830
Rick March: you know, I let them, when it was a rainy day and they couldn't go out on the playground for recess, I let them, you know, bring in their records and, you know.

221
00:34:22.749 --> 00:34:25.189
Rick March: Things like that. I let them.

222
00:34:25.190 --> 00:34:27.009
Julie Stout: What did you… wait, what did you teach?

223
00:34:27.489 --> 00:34:29.249
Rick March: 6th grade.

224
00:34:29.719 --> 00:34:32.109
Julie Stout: Oh, good! Like, 6th grade what?

225
00:34:32.449 --> 00:34:34.929
Rick March: 6th grade, everything. There wasn't middle school then.

226
00:34:34.929 --> 00:34:36.079
Julie Stout: Oh!

227
00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:41.319
Rick March: K6, and then junior high was 7 through 9, and high school was 10, 11, 12.

228
00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:44.619
Julie Stout: I see, I see. 6th grade, everything.

229
00:34:44.620 --> 00:34:48.089
Rick March: So those were the oldest kids in the, in the elementary school.

230
00:34:48.090 --> 00:34:49.020
Julie Stout: Mmm.

231
00:34:49.020 --> 00:35:02.609
Rick March: And and I… I only… there was a… there was a, you know, a certified teacher that would come in that was assigned to three of us. The program, I assume, is called the Talent Search Program.

232
00:35:02.610 --> 00:35:12.969
Rick March: There were, like, people who were talented at teaching, and he would come in, and he would show a, you know, he would show me how to create a particular lesson plan, and then he'd watch me do it, you know.

233
00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:18.829
Rick March: And, about a third of the time, and then the other two-thirds, he was in the other two people's classrooms.

234
00:35:18.990 --> 00:35:25.980
Rick March: And, and, you know, I was… I…

235
00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:42.289
Rick March: basically, they gave me the opportunity to quit, or they were gonna fire me at a certain point. You know, like, I had said, instead of letting the kids… all the kids I knew lined up when the bell rang from the playground, and had to line up in order of height.

236
00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:56.110
Rick March: Tallest first, shortest at the end, and then they had to, you know, I had to come downstairs and leave them into the school building, and they had to be one arm's length from the right-hand side of the hallway.

237
00:35:56.530 --> 00:36:15.960
Rick March: And so, you know, you know, stupid young guy, I just said, hey, you kids are sixth graders, you're the oldest kids, you know how to come into the, you know, classroom without causing any disturbance, right? So I'm not going to come and lead you in. You know, you just, you know, when the bell rings, just come up quietly and come to the classroom.

238
00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:26.660
Rick March: Okay, that lasted one day. You know, things like that, that I, I, so, so anyway, I got, I got fired.

239
00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:28.250
Julie Stout: Wait, how long did you work there for, then?

240
00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:34.770
Rick March: Oh, no, no, no, it didn't last that long, it was, like, 8 weeks, you know, or something.

241
00:36:34.770 --> 00:36:36.650
Julie Stout: Oh, so it was fast!

242
00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:47.780
Rick March: Yeah, yeah, so then I thought, oh shit, now what do I do? And I got advice from a guy who is a lawyer who is advising young guys like me on how to,

243
00:36:47.940 --> 00:36:51.159
Rick March: Resist the draft, legally.

244
00:36:52.390 --> 00:37:00.299
Rick March: And he said, you know, you gotta tangle up the Selective Service people with all of their bureaucratic regulations as much as you can.

245
00:37:00.430 --> 00:37:17.059
Rick March: And, for example, with any communication you get from them, you have 30 days to respond. Wait 29 days, then send… respond with a registered letter. So, when they… they sent me my 1A classification, because I was no longer in college, he said, okay.

246
00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:22.519
Rick March: Send them a letter that says, I appeal my classification. Do not say anything else.

247
00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:23.709
Rick March: In that letter.

248
00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:26.819
Rick March: And, so, you know, wait 29 days, I send it.

249
00:37:27.130 --> 00:37:32.070
Rick March: So then they had to send back a letter saying, you know, on what grounds are you appealing it?

250
00:37:32.850 --> 00:37:50.130
Rick March: And so, at that point, the lawyer said, hey, is there any state that you can go live in other than California, where you registered, for the draft? And I said, yeah, my brother lives in Wisconsin. My eldest brother was a physics professor in Wisconsin at that point.

251
00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:54.380
Rick March: And so I said, Yeah, I could go to Wisconsin. He said, go there.

252
00:37:54.850 --> 00:37:58.510
Rick March: So, from Wisconsin, you know,

253
00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:03.179
Rick March: I was able to, you know, again, tie them up, And then…

254
00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:12.559
Rick March: request that instead of having the California Appeal Board handle my appeal, the Wisconsin Draft Appeal Board could handle it.

255
00:38:12.890 --> 00:38:13.240
Julie Stout: Hmm.

256
00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:22.019
Rick March: And California was having a ton of… a ton of hippies that were saying that they were conscientious objectors, meaning that, you know, I'm against all violence.

257
00:38:22.120 --> 00:38:30.419
Rick March: And I am. But they were only recognizing people that were either Quakers or Jehovah's Witnesses, you know, in California.

258
00:38:30.500 --> 00:38:49.809
Rick March: And they weren't familiar with that whole scene yet at the draft board and the appeal board in Wisconsin. So, I was able, in Wisconsin, to… they didn't give me the conscientious objector status, but they gave me a status called 1Y, which means we could take you if we want you, but

259
00:38:49.810 --> 00:39:01.699
Rick March: at this point, we don't want you… yet. So, and that never changed for, you know, that never, never changed. So I got the, the, my, my going to… moving to Wisconsin.

260
00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:08.929
Rick March: got me out of the draft. In the meanwhile, then, I met my girlfriend, who later became my first wife.

261
00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:10.560
Rick March: And,

262
00:39:10.780 --> 00:39:18.109
Rick March: you know, I took her at a certain point out to California, and we lived in California for

263
00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:20.199
Rick March: You know, several months.

264
00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:22.300
Rick March: And she didn't like it.

265
00:39:22.750 --> 00:39:23.590
Julie Stout: Mmm…

266
00:39:23.590 --> 00:39:24.709
Rick March: He didn't like it.

267
00:39:24.870 --> 00:39:35.660
Rick March: And then… and then I had the, idea to go to what was then Yugoslavia, you know, Croatia was part of a bigger state called Yugoslavia at that time.

268
00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:49.130
Rick March: And, she and I went there, and I studied… I went and I enrolled in a program called Ethnology, which was, you know, kind of like Anthro, except in Europe.

269
00:39:49.360 --> 00:40:03.039
Rick March: the European Ethnology Department study their own nation's culture, for the most part. You know, we're different than anthropologists who tend to study, you know, at that time especially, cultures that were exotic from there.

270
00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:04.900
Rick March: So…

271
00:40:05.010 --> 00:40:11.930
Rick March: So, I studied for 3 semesters there. I started a band. Oh, where did… where did you go to school?

272
00:40:12.280 --> 00:40:14.380
Rick March: University of Zagreb.

273
00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:14.870
Julie Stout: Mmm.

274
00:40:14.870 --> 00:40:25.729
Rick March: University of Zagreb, and I was in the ethnology Department, and, you know, my wife and I, got a, a rented room.

275
00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:38.770
Rick March: My family was all living down at the seacoast, which is, you know, pretty far from Zagreb on the island where my mom was from. So I would go down there and visit relatives sometimes, but, you know, I didn't have…

276
00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:40.239
Julie Stout: Jude! Oh, I'm so sorry.

277
00:40:40.240 --> 00:40:40.809
Rick March: Go ahead.

278
00:40:41.050 --> 00:40:47.620
Julie Stout: Did you, know your relatives from before as well, or were you meeting these people for the first time?

279
00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:59.980
Rick March: I met them for the first time when, let's see, it would have been 1967. I was about 19 was my first trip, and I met relatives in the home village.

280
00:40:59.980 --> 00:41:00.970
Julie Stout: Okay.

281
00:41:00.970 --> 00:41:10.059
Rick March: And then, yeah, so I, I, I, I bought a, a moped, if you know what one of those are.

282
00:41:10.060 --> 00:41:10.910
Julie Stout: Like, the scooters?

283
00:41:10.910 --> 00:41:23.359
Rick March: I bought a moped, which at maximum speed, you go about 25 miles an hour, and I used it to commute down to, you know, the village, you know.

284
00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:23.850
Julie Stout: Oh, God!

285
00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:37.299
Rick March: Or, you know, my wife didn't wind up staying. She got homesick and went back and was living with her mother. It wasn't a marital breakup at that point, but it was a kind of a sign of things to come, I think.

286
00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:37.870
Julie Stout: Hmm.

287
00:41:37.870 --> 00:41:50.570
Rick March: You know, and, but, so, yeah, when my wife was still there, we took her bus and the ferry boat and so forth, but when I was on my own, then I just, you know, took the moped.

288
00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:57.790
Julie Stout: Was your… was your family, like, still speaking Croatian at that point? Or was it mostly English, or…

289
00:41:57.790 --> 00:42:04.710
Rick March: Well, which… the part of the family that was in… in, Yugoslavia was, of course, still speaking Croatian. My…

290
00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:11.020
Rick March: After my mother… my grandmother died, my mother's mother died when I was 13.

291
00:42:11.020 --> 00:42:11.970
Julie Stout: Mmm.

292
00:42:12.220 --> 00:42:19.000
Rick March: And then my Aunt Marisa was still living with us for a while. After… after she moved out.

293
00:42:19.090 --> 00:42:36.220
Rick March: And it was just my mother and me and my elder brother, English started to take over as the dominant language in the household, whereas Croatian had been more dominant when there was, you know, my mother

294
00:42:36.300 --> 00:42:41.260
Rick March: her sister and her mother, there were, like, 3 native Croatian speakers in the family.

295
00:42:41.670 --> 00:42:51.039
Rick March: there's me that had gotten it, you know, to a degree, as, you know, we kids would answer back in English often, you know?

296
00:42:51.420 --> 00:42:55.139
Rick March: Yeah, I, you know, we… they'd say someday, you know, she'd…

297
00:42:55.410 --> 00:43:13.829
Rick March: she'd say, you know, you know, she'd… my grandmother tell me, you know, buddy, it's time for you to go to bed, you know, or whatever, and I'd say, no, no, no, no, we called our grandmother Nona. No, no, no, I don't… you know, I'm not sleepy yet. You know, I'd say that in English, you know, whatever.

298
00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:15.429
Rick March: But,

299
00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:36.729
Rick March: But, you know, I spoke a dialect, an island dialect that I learned from home, and it was quite an adaption to learn the literary language, especially on an academic level, because what I learned was talk about, you know, what's for supper, you know.

300
00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:38.960
