01:23:18.130 --> 01:23:35.409
Rick March: it took a while to… because you had to have matching funds and stuff, it took a while to develop an organization that wanted to have a full-time folk arts, you know, state folklorist, and it turned out to be the Wisconsin Arts Board. And, you know, I applied for it, and I got the first

628
01:23:35.410 --> 01:23:48.290
Rick March: you know, crack at it, which was cool, because there never had been a state folklorist, and so I got to make up what a state… you know, as long as I could present the ideas to my director and to the board.

629
01:23:48.460 --> 01:23:50.919
Rick March: And they said, oh, okay, that's good.

630
01:23:51.120 --> 01:24:04.240
Rick March: you know, I got to invent it. And so I involved a lot of field work and so forth in the process, and then Bess had also created the apprenticeship program the very first year that I started.

631
01:24:04.830 --> 01:24:18.219
Rick March: first year of what was called Folk Arts Apprenticeships, and they were run out of D.C. at first. Everybody had to apply to the NEA, and it turned out to be totally unworkable. And so she farmed it out to the states.

632
01:24:18.300 --> 01:24:26.699
Rick March: And so I, you know, was in the first year that the states had it, and she asked people to have a specialization.

633
01:24:26.700 --> 01:24:29.200
Julie Stout: And I had met some people at a…

634
01:24:29.200 --> 01:24:36.900
Rick March: at a, native, you know, tribal arts festival in Eau Claire, Wisconsin.

635
01:24:37.550 --> 01:24:41.199
Rick March: they… I talked about, hey, I got this apprenticeship program.

636
01:24:41.670 --> 01:24:58.979
Rick March: what do you think if we put an emphasis, you know, on native traditions as the focus? You know, some people didn't have any, but Bess was encouraging a focus, so then that gave me a reason to work with the 11 tribes and bands, plus the urban Indians in Milwaukee.

637
01:24:59.280 --> 01:25:04.849
Rick March: And, and then, you know.

638
01:25:05.150 --> 01:25:20.040
Rick March: that developed a whole set of, you know, associations, and, you know, I was always very careful as a government guy to never promise more than I could deliver. So if I was saying, you know, yeah, there are some grants, but

639
01:25:20.200 --> 01:25:25.660
Rick March: I'm not deciding, you know, there's a panel of people. I can give you advice on how to write this.

640
01:25:25.810 --> 01:25:36.829
Rick March: I can give you advice on how to budget it, but, you know, you may get it, you may not. And, and so I was… I was always very careful, and… and I also, you know.

641
01:25:36.870 --> 01:25:50.170
Rick March: I had learned enough… I think that my… growing up in these kind of multiple cultural settings, you know, living with the people from Missouri who were, you know, I jokingly called them, intellectual rednecks.

642
01:25:50.190 --> 01:26:02.570
Rick March: Because, you know, they were… they were from a very much, you know, Highland South culture of Missouri, but they were individuals who read a lot of, like, philosophy books and things.

643
01:26:02.570 --> 01:26:03.170
Julie Stout: Mmm.

644
01:26:03.170 --> 01:26:07.869
Rick March: and, the…

645
01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:15.149
Rick March: you know, what I liked about being on the farm was, you know, every meal was a big discussion, you know?

646
01:26:15.150 --> 01:26:15.890
Julie Stout: We'd sit there.

647
01:26:15.890 --> 01:26:35.479
Rick March: and discuss, you know, all sorts of stuff. And so, you know, I… I knew how they were different culturally, and I could fit in with them in their, you know, essentially upland South Missouri culture. Then my, my, my fam… my own family's Croatian culture,

648
01:26:35.600 --> 01:26:50.890
Rick March: I went to this Unitarian church where there were a lot of youth group kids who were from a variety of backgrounds, including a lot of Jewish kids. My dad was Jewish. My dad… my dad was an atheist.

649
01:26:51.000 --> 01:27:03.740
Rick March: and minimized his Jewish connections, because he said, well, you know, Judaism's a religion, and, you know, my family's from Poland and Lithuania, you know?

650
01:27:04.910 --> 01:27:18.929
Rick March: you know, he wasn't interested in that. But, you know, I knew just, again, because of, you know, who were a lot of the political radicals, a lot of them were from Jewish background.

651
01:27:18.930 --> 01:27:23.170
Julie Stout: And so I already, just growing up, had these multiple cultures that.

652
01:27:23.410 --> 01:27:41.409
Rick March: you know, I navigated in. And then, you know, doing field work in Gary, doing… and, you know, I wasn't only… the part of Chicago we lived in, in the Kenwood neighborhood, was one of the few, kind of.

653
01:27:41.450 --> 01:27:55.999
Rick March: racially integrated area, so I, you know, I was used to dealing with Black kids, you know, growing up. And, so, you know, I was helping John Hassey, you know, working in the Black community. Not that I had any, you know, you know, it was just that

654
01:27:56.230 --> 01:28:03.350
Rick March: I was at ease in Black communities where, you know, John, who… who,

655
01:28:03.520 --> 01:28:08.879
Rick March: you know, grew up out in, was it South Dakota, or,

656
01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:20.909
Rick March: trying to remember. I know he went to college in, you know, rural Minnesota, and so on and so forth, and was just fascinated by Black people, but didn't have much experience with them.

657
01:28:20.910 --> 01:28:21.780
Julie Stout: You know?

658
01:28:21.780 --> 01:28:32.009
Rick March: So… so again, you know, I… I was just very fortunate that my life path took me into contact with a lot of different cultures, and… and then…

659
01:28:32.160 --> 01:28:42.810
Rick March: Wisconsin is a very culturally diverse state, despite being, you know, well, more than 80% white, but the…

660
01:28:43.110 --> 01:28:49.100
Rick March: specific European traditions have remained very strong.

661
01:28:49.660 --> 01:28:54.409
Rick March: generations, people are very conscious of being German-American, or Polish-American, or

662
01:28:54.850 --> 01:28:58.760
Rick March: American, you know, and it still relates to

663
01:28:59.160 --> 01:29:07.410
Rick March: social life, like, you play different card games. If you're a Norwegian-American, you play Euchre, but if you're a German-American, you play Sheep's Head, which is another.

664
01:29:07.410 --> 01:29:08.140
Julie Stout: or.

665
01:29:08.140 --> 01:29:15.640
Rick March: Belgians play a game called Kuyu. You know, like, even these card games have persisted in ethnic context.

666
01:29:16.010 --> 01:29:18.620
Rick March: And, and then,

667
01:29:18.920 --> 01:29:23.020
Rick March: One of the things I did when I worked on the farm is,

668
01:29:23.330 --> 01:29:39.269
Rick March: this guy, Bob Pepper, that I stayed with, he took a job for a while working for, the Farm Workers Union over in Modesto, and so I went over there with him, and I worked, you know, farm work jobs, mostly with Mexicans.

669
01:29:39.610 --> 01:29:42.259
Rick March: No Mexican-Americans, for the most part.

670
01:29:42.450 --> 01:29:46.020
Rick March: And,

671
01:29:46.170 --> 01:29:56.120
Rick March: the Unitarian youth group went down to Mexico one summer, and I went with them. We stayed in Jalisco, in a little town where a rich lady who was a member of the congregation

672
01:29:56.200 --> 01:30:14.669
Rick March: owned a, an orphanage, and we… they're, making an irrigation system for the orchard. They were… so, you know, I spent a summer in Mexico, even though I took French in high school, which was… Well, whatever, I can speak some French. I learned a lot of Spanish, and…

673
01:30:14.670 --> 01:30:15.110
Julie Stout: Meaning.

674
01:30:15.110 --> 01:30:25.169
Rick March: And… and plus being in California, you're around a lot of… a lot of kids that were Spanish-speaking. So, you know, I… I just… I just was lucky to have this,

675
01:30:25.680 --> 01:30:37.749
Rick March: plethora of cultural inputs into my life that made me comfortable with, plunging myself into… You know, my big brother, who…

676
01:30:38.200 --> 01:30:51.480
Rick March: he's passed away now, I can speak a little bit this way, who tended to be a socially awkward guy. He was a really brilliant genius physicist, but, he was probably… he was… he was,

677
01:30:52.240 --> 01:30:58.710
Rick March: You know, bullied a bit and marginalized as a brain in those days, you know, when you…

678
01:30:58.710 --> 01:30:59.400
Julie Stout: wrong.

679
01:30:59.400 --> 01:31:14.710
Rick March: You know, and so, he, he said, oh, you know, my little brother here, you know, if the Martians landed, he'd be, he'd be sitting there, you know, hanging out, learning Martian customs, you know. He said, what's about me?

680
01:31:15.900 --> 01:31:16.990
Rick March: Whatever.

681
01:31:18.290 --> 01:31:27.339
Rick March: whatever. So anyway, this is kind of… this kind of, you know, I think we've… we've talked longer than… than the hour and a half, but I don't want to…

682
01:31:27.640 --> 01:31:31.690
Julie Stout: No, it's okay. Yeah, my,

683
01:31:32.190 --> 01:31:35.850
Julie Stout: How long did you act as State Focalist for Wisconsin again?

684
01:31:35.850 --> 01:31:36.940
Rick March: 26 years.

685
01:31:36.940 --> 01:31:38.550
Julie Stout: 26 years.

686
01:31:38.550 --> 01:31:42.869
Rick March: I… I was offered being deputy director of the.

687
01:31:42.870 --> 01:31:43.370
Julie Stout: agency.

688
01:31:43.370 --> 01:31:44.600
Rick March: two times.

689
01:31:44.840 --> 01:31:46.139
Rick March: And,

690
01:31:46.320 --> 01:31:58.609
Rick March: you know, I was thinking about it, you know, it was some more money, and I went to talk to another guy who had been a folklorist who had… in Indiana, I think, yeah. Jeff, god, what was his last name?

691
01:31:58.930 --> 01:32:08.190
Rick March: I forget now. Anyway, I was at a regional folklore gathering, and I asked him, I said, well, you know, you went ahead and took, like, a deputy director job.

692
01:32:08.190 --> 01:32:19.150
Rick March: you know, how do you like it? They said, well, you know, you have to make up your mind. Do you want to, you know, continue being a folklorist, or are you interested in being an arts administrator?

693
01:32:19.660 --> 01:32:23.130
Rick March: And I said, thank you, you answered my question.

694
01:32:24.430 --> 01:32:26.049
Rick March: And.

695
01:32:26.050 --> 01:32:26.640
Julie Stout: Here we go.

696
01:32:26.640 --> 01:32:47.130
Rick March: And I, you know, I actually realized, deputy director, you get all the tasks that the director doesn't want to do. You had to do, like, annual performance or 6 months performance evaluations of your co-workers. You had to, you know, you were stuck in the office, you were, you were, you know, answering voicemail and emails all the time, you know.

697
01:32:47.130 --> 01:32:48.440
Julie Stout: Administrative stuff, yeah.

698
01:32:48.440 --> 01:33:04.039
Rick March: Yeah, yeah, you know, going over, you know, all kinds of, you know, forms and shit. And and so, you know, they off… I turned it down that time. Then a couple years later, they offered it to me again, and I… after I turned it down the second time for a different director.

699
01:33:04.170 --> 01:33:06.519
Rick March: They realized, oh, this guy, you know…

700
01:33:06.810 --> 01:33:09.130
Rick March: He, he, you know, we, we, you know.

701
01:33:09.330 --> 01:33:14.320
Rick March: It wasn't enough money to make me want to stop, you know, being in the field.

702
01:33:14.320 --> 01:33:14.660
Julie Stout: Yeah.

703
01:33:14.660 --> 01:33:18.010
Rick March: And, it was just…

704
01:33:18.330 --> 01:33:23.910
Rick March: I can say that until the very end, when I was really ready to retire.

705
01:33:24.470 --> 01:33:28.159
Rick March: that I never got up in the morning and said.

706
01:33:28.220 --> 01:33:30.500
Rick March: Ugh, I have to go to work.

707
01:33:30.500 --> 01:33:51.930
Rick March: it was always like, oh, I can hardly wait to get down to the office, because, you know, I gotta see how that thing, you know, with the group up at Eau Claire is happening. You know, I hated it when they started clamping down more bureaucratically. I knew what my travel budget for the year was, and I'd stretch it, you know, in a way that was a little, a little on the, you know, edgy side.

708
01:33:51.930 --> 01:33:57.259
Rick March: people invite me to stay, so I said, I'm gonna save, you know, the hotel money.

709
01:33:57.260 --> 01:34:07.019
Rick March: You know, if it wasn't somebody that was directly applying for a grant or something, you know, I'd stay with somebody and, you know, when I had to be overnight.

710
01:34:07.040 --> 01:34:12.789
Rick March: there were, you know, all kinds of ways.

711
01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:15.820
Rick March: that, you know, I liked the fact

712
01:34:15.990 --> 01:34:35.459
Rick March: that, like, okay, so the Arts Council in Wausau, in central Wisconsin, would call me up, you know, let's just say, hey, you know, Rick, there, we're having a big board meeting coming up, or we have to make some decisions about X, Y, and Z, you know, because again, it was folk and community, so I was dealing with the community arts broader than just folk arts.

713
01:34:35.460 --> 01:34:52.089
Rick March: They said, we, you know, could you attend our board meeting and give us some advice and discussion of these… these issues? And so, you know, I say, okay, when is it? And they'd say, you know, yeah, next week, Thursday, blah blah blah. I'd look at… I'd look at my calendar, I'd look at my travel budget.

714
01:34:52.530 --> 01:34:57.120
Rick March: And I'd… I'd be able to tell them, yes, yeah, I can make it.

715
01:34:58.220 --> 01:35:11.040
Rick March: Then, you know, the Department of Administration for the state started clamping down, and so, in order to go to that meeting in Wausau, I would have had to fill out a bunch of forms. It would say.

716
01:35:11.150 --> 01:35:18.610
Rick March: What agency goals and objectives are you fulfilling by attending this meeting?

717
01:35:18.610 --> 01:35:19.480
Julie Stout: Mmm…

718
01:35:19.480 --> 01:35:37.369
Rick March: And, you know, when is it? How much is it gonna cost? And then you had to pass that memo along to somebody at the Department of Administration, and wait for them to approve it. And it might take 2 weeks, you know, and they usually approved it, but sometimes they didn't.

719
01:35:37.370 --> 01:35:47.579
Rick March: you know, I mean, I knew how to write bureaucratic bullshit enough to fit it in with one of the goals and objectives of the agency, so it usually would pass, but, you know, it was like…

720
01:35:47.700 --> 01:35:54.129
Rick March: I started to hate the increasing, you know, control level that.

721
01:35:54.130 --> 01:35:54.560
Julie Stout: Oh, my God.

722
01:35:54.560 --> 01:35:56.899
Rick March: you know, I felt like, hey.

723
01:35:57.970 --> 01:36:11.910
Rick March: I know how to represent my agency. You know, I go to the board meetings, I know what our agency objectives are. I know, I know what my budget is. I'm not gonna go over budget.

724
01:36:11.910 --> 01:36:16.840
Julie Stout: If I run out of travel money before the end of the fiscal year.

725
01:36:16.840 --> 01:36:24.869
Rick March: that's, you know, that's terrible, because it means I can't go anywhere for, you know, for months. So, you know, I figured it out.

726
01:36:26.280 --> 01:36:34.610
Rick March: So anyway, that gives you an idea, then, of, you know, why I stayed in the… as the folklorist.

727
01:36:35.350 --> 01:36:43.380
Rick March: And I also, eventually, when I hit 62, I was really,

728
01:36:43.570 --> 01:36:47.820
Rick March: one of the things I couldn't do, I had some books in mind that I wanted to write.

729
01:36:48.510 --> 01:37:06.539
Rick March: And, when I hit 62 and was eligible to go, you know, on pension and so forth, I took early retirement. I didn't wait till 65. And I also felt it was good for us to open up some of these folklorist jobs to younger colleagues, because, you know.

730
01:37:06.770 --> 01:37:08.180
Rick March: I, I could do it!

731
01:37:08.530 --> 01:37:09.910
Julie Stout: Yeah, yeah.

732
01:37:09.910 --> 01:37:21.339
Rick March: I could do it. So, you know, so I retired and, you know, I wrote the folklore, the two folklore books first, one on Croatian music, and then one on polka.

733
01:37:21.380 --> 01:37:33.980
Rick March: And they got published, and then my wife, my second wife, I'd gotten divorced, and I met a woman in Wisconsin who was a history professor, and we're…

734
01:37:33.980 --> 01:37:45.810
Rick March: We're now married for 20 years, and you know, very compatible. And she urged me to write about my family's history, and I did. I wrote a book that got published,

735
01:37:45.910 --> 01:37:52.769
Rick March: called A Great Vision about our, you know, growing up in a radical family, the stuff I've been talking about, except in

736
01:37:52.980 --> 01:37:58.739
Rick March: different emphases. A lot of it emphasized my dad's, you know, days as a union organizer. He survived.

737
01:37:58.740 --> 01:37:59.460
Julie Stout: Hmm.

738
01:37:59.460 --> 01:38:02.720
Rick March: Nation attempts and stuff, so it has some dramatic things.

739
01:38:04.180 --> 01:38:20.240
Rick March: So I wrote, I retired at 62, and I wrote the three books, and got them published in the 6 years, and I said, oh shit, now what do I do? But I've been doing some more writing, and I've been doing some… I also, if you're curious.

740
01:38:20.780 --> 01:38:34.930
Rick March: I wound up producing about 10 YouTube videos on vintage Japanese music. I started a music program at the senior lunch where singers, you know, I met 3 other people who play music.

741
01:38:34.930 --> 01:38:47.739
Rick March: And then some of the immigrants from Japan, you know, they miss singing songs that they learned as kids at school, or that were on the radio when they were in Japan before they emigrated.

742
01:38:47.740 --> 01:38:48.150
Julie Stout: Yeah.

743
01:38:48.150 --> 01:39:02.590
Rick March: And so they suggested songs, and my friend John doesn't mind spending hours on the computer finding the words and music to these songs, and we print them out, and we do these things. So I learned quite a bit about vintage Japanese music.

744
01:39:02.740 --> 01:39:03.969
Rick March: And,

745
01:39:04.290 --> 01:39:12.889
Rick March: somebody brought in, you know, there's a lot… a table with giveaway stuff at the senior lunch. Somebody brought in a box of old 78 discs.

746
01:39:13.150 --> 01:39:14.179
Julie Stout: Of Japanese music.

747
01:39:14.180 --> 01:39:24.519
Rick March: And of course, you know, I had a program called Down Home Dairyland on Wisconsin Public Radio for over 30 years, actually. I continued it, actually, when I was in Oregon still.

748
01:39:26.070 --> 01:39:38.949
Rick March: So I took the 78s home, and, you know, the ones that were in decent shape, I made digital recordings of, and the director of the lunch program said, hey, what do those records sound like?

749
01:39:39.050 --> 01:39:41.879
Rick March: And I thought, oh, I could send her some files, and I thought.

750
01:39:41.880 --> 01:39:42.460
Julie Stout: Yeah.

751
01:39:42.460 --> 01:39:56.700
Rick March: I'm gonna make a fake radio program using those files. And so I asked my wife to record a fake station ID. You're listening to Radio WINK, the voice of a corny guy. Dong, dong, dong, you know.

752
01:39:56.700 --> 01:39:57.170
Julie Stout: Yeah.

753
01:39:57.170 --> 01:39:58.870
Rick March: Thomasana, Japanese instrument.

754
01:39:58.900 --> 01:40:09.079
Rick March: And so, anyway, I made this fake radio program and made a selection of those records. And people really liked it. She put it on, like, the sound system in the room.

755
01:40:09.080 --> 01:40:23.239
Rick March: People really liked it. And a younger woman, Ame Hayashi, who was coming occasionally to the senior lunch she was working, she had flexible hours because she and her husband were working on a biography of a famous sumo wrestler.

756
01:40:23.240 --> 01:40:27.110
Rick March: Oh! Yeah. Yeah. So, anyway.

757
01:40:27.200 --> 01:40:39.520
Rick March: I think she's still under 40. So, you know, people in your generation are able to make videos, you know, in their sleep, I think. So she said, I can turn your soundtracks into videos.

758
01:40:42.210 --> 01:40:58.959
Rick March: And I said, well, let's go for it. And so she found stills and videos, video clips, of these vintage artists from the 30s, 40s, 50s, you know, and we put them… put them on YouTube, on the ecoinda card, the lunch program, as a YouTube channel.

759
01:40:59.460 --> 01:41:06.550
Rick March: And so we put them on there, and I started getting favorable comments. I got comments from Japan, you know.

760
01:41:07.730 --> 01:41:19.960
Rick March: Sometimes written in English, sometimes in Japanese, and you know, they're saying, oh, we have nothing like this in Japan, you know, and okay, good.

761
01:41:21.240 --> 01:41:23.830
Rick March: And

762
01:41:24.020 --> 01:41:34.449
Rick March: Yeah, so I'd encourage you, you know, I can, I can email you a link, to, to the Koinokai, YouTube channel.

763
01:41:34.450 --> 01:41:34.950
Julie Stout: Yes, please.

764
01:41:34.950 --> 01:41:46.070
Rick March: So my last burst of creativity after I finally stopped making Down Home Dairyland programs, I stopped after my 76th birthday.

765
01:41:46.070 --> 01:41:46.480
Julie Stout: I decided.

766
01:41:46.480 --> 01:41:53.570
Rick March: You know, I'm just getting a little tired of having to produce 4 or 5 hours of radio a month.

767
01:41:53.900 --> 01:41:54.330
Julie Stout: news.

768
01:41:54.330 --> 01:42:00.669
Rick March: you know, public stations in Wisconsin. I was just doing it for free.

769
01:42:00.670 --> 01:42:01.410
Julie Stout: Mmm.

770
01:42:02.100 --> 01:42:10.460
Rick March: And some of the stations are still playing my reruns, but I also helped recruit a younger woman who's, you know, doing… who's mostly polka.

771
01:42:10.840 --> 01:42:11.500
Julie Stout: Hmm.

772
01:42:11.500 --> 01:42:12.320
Rick March: And,

773
01:42:12.680 --> 01:42:21.880
Rick March: But, my last big burst of creativity was on making, you know, learning a whole bunch about vintage Japanese music and making these videos.

774
01:42:22.240 --> 01:42:24.100
Julie Stout: Yeah, no, I love that, yeah.

775
01:42:24.610 --> 01:42:34.390
Rick March: Yeah, so yeah, you might want to watch one of them, or whatever. One of them… one of them was related to a singer that was being featured on a… on a,

776
01:42:34.660 --> 01:42:39.400
Rick March: Japanese TV Morning Cereal program, you know, where they.

777
01:42:39.400 --> 01:42:39.840
Julie Stout: Mmm.

778
01:42:39.840 --> 01:42:44.950
Rick March: Of, like, they had 20 minutes a day on the story of this person's life.

779
01:42:44.950 --> 01:42:48.090
Julie Stout: And so I made a… I made a program about her.

780
01:42:48.090 --> 01:42:53.740
Rick March: And that one got 9,000 views, you know, you know, which, you know, pretty good for a…

781
01:42:53.740 --> 01:42:54.499
Julie Stout: That's pretty good!

782
01:42:54.670 --> 01:43:09.579
